<br>
Secondly, it is based on the fact that most boss MOBs that people would like to raid are targets of opportunity that rarely pop up, and that you must quickly react to.<br>
<br>
I think everyone did a great job in reacting to Severilous on Saturday. However, this was mostly due to the fact there were several porters on who wanted to be part of the raid, and helped bring people there. What happens the day that everyone's gung-ho, but all the porters are lazy, working on their epics or something? Since it's in the middle of nowhere, without the porters that raid wouldn't have happened. <br>
<br>
That said, raid job requirements are really something that should be based on a guild's mission statement. I tend to think that *requirement* is kind of harsh and unnecessary if a guild is functioning well and taking down MOBs consistently and efficiently - especially when a guild's mission statement is:<br>
<br>
&quot;Ours is a guild based on trust and honor more than anything else. We don't invite &quot;characters&quot; into Amazon, we invite PEOPLE.&quot;<br>
<br>
In other words it's not a guild based on uberness and getting the best loot.<br>
<br>
That said, getting in the mindset that everyone has a specific job cannot hurt. In my opinion, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">when people decide they want to attend a raid they should have certain jobs *written down* that they must fulfill in terms of organization</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> - just like everyone has specific jobs when you're actually engaging the MOB.<br>
<br>
I mean let's face it, once you get to the 50+ levels raiding is a huge part of EQ whether or not your a family-oriented guild. So why not make the guild as efficient as possible at it? That's how you become the envy of all Xegony. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
